        // If p_i is not the smallest value, then max_val_in_row will be p_i.
        // The only exception is if p_i = n. In that case, max_val_in_row will be n-1.
        // So, p_i is either max_val_in_row or n.
        // We can determine if p_i is n by checking if max_val_in_row is less than n.
        // If max_val_in_row is less than n, then p_i must be n.
        // Otherwise, p_i is max_val_in_row.

        // This logic is simpler: p_i is the maximum value in its row (excluding a_i,i)
        // UNLESS p_i is n. If p_i is n, then for all j != i, p_j < n, so min(p_i, p_j) = p_j.
        // In this case, max_val_in_row will be max(p_j for j!=i) which is n-1.
        // So, if max_val_in_row is n-1, p_i could be n.
        // If max_val_in_row is less than n-1, then p_i must be max_val_in_row.
        // The problem states that there is at least one solution.
        // The simplest way to reconstruct p_i is to take the maximum value in row i.
        // If this maximum value is less than n, then p_i must be n.
        // Otherwise, p_i is that maximum value.

        // Let's re-evaluate:
        // For a given i, p_i is either the maximum value in row i (excluding a_i,i)
        // OR p_i is n, and the maximum value in row i (excluding a_i,i) is n-1.
        // This means if max_val_in_row == n-1, p_i could be n.
        // If max_val_in_row < n-1, then p_i must be max_val_in_row.
        // The problem guarantees a solution.
        // The value 'n' must appear exactly once in the permutation.
        // If we find a row where max_val_in_row is n-1, that's a candidate for p_i = n.
        // If there are multiple such rows, only one can be n.
        // The simplest approach is to assign p_i = max_val_in_row for all i.
        // Then, if the value 'n' is missing from the reconstructed permutation,
        // it means the actual 'n' was hidden as an 'n-1' in some row.
        // In that case, we find the maximum value in the reconstructed permutation
        // (which would be n-1) and change it to n.

        p[i] = max_val_in_row;
    }

    bool n_found = false;
    for (int val : p) {
        if (val == n) {
            n_found = true;
            break;
        }
    }

    if (!n_found) {
        // If n is not found, it means the actual 'n' was represented as 'n-1'
        // in the max_val_in_row calculation.
        // We need to find the maximum value in the current 'p' array (which will be n-1)
        // and change it to n.
        int max_p_val = 0;
        int max_p_idx = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            if (p[i] > max_p_val) {
                max_p_val = p[i];
                max_p_idx = i;
            }
        }
        // max_p_val should be n-1 here.
        p[max_p_idx] = n;
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cout << p[i] << (i == n - 1 ? "" : " ");
    }
    std::cout << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

