    // We need `A != C` (i.e., `A` is not a palindrome) and `B` is a palindrome.
    // If these conditions hold, then `CBA` is a palindrome and `CBA != ABC`.
    // This requires 2 cuts.

    // Check for k=2
    // Iterate `i` from 1 up to `n/2`.
    // `i` is the length of the prefix `A`.
    // `A = s.substr(0, i)`
    // `B = s.substr(i, n - 2*i)`
    // `C = s.substr(n - i, i)`
    // We need `A != C` (which means `A` is not a palindrome) AND `B` is a palindrome.
    // If `A` is not a palindrome, then `A != reverse(A)`.
    // Since `s` is a palindrome, `A = reverse(C)`.
    // So `A != C` is equivalent to `A != reverse(A)`, i.e., `A` is not a palindrome.
    // So we need to find `i` such that `s.substr(0, i)` is NOT a palindrome AND `s.substr(i, n - 2*i)` IS a palindrome.
    // The length of `B` is `n - 2*i`. This must be >= 0.
    // If `n - 2*i == 0`, `B` is empty, which is a palindrome.
    // If `n - 2*i == 1`, `B` is a single character, which is a palindrome.
    for (int i = 1; i <= n / 2; ++i) {
        std::string prefix = s.substr(0, i);
        std::string middle = s.substr(i, n - 2 * i);

        if (!is_palindrome(prefix) && is_palindrome(middle)) {
            std::cout << 2 << std::endl;
            return 0;
        }
    }

    // If neither k=1 nor k=2 works, it's impossible.
    // This happens if all prefixes s[0...i-1] are palindromes for i <= n/2,
    // AND for all such i, s[i...n-1-i] is not a palindrome.
    // The condition "all prefixes s[0...i-1] are palindromes for i <= n/2"
    // implies that s must be composed of repeating characters, e.g., "aaaaa", "abaaba".
    // If s consists of all same characters (e.g., "qqqq"), then any prefix is a palindrome.
    // In this case, `s.substr(i, n - 2*i)` will also be all same characters, hence a palindrome.
    // So for "qqqq", `i=1`: prefix="q" (pal), middle="qq" (pal). This would output 2.
    // But "qqqq" is Impossible.
    // The issue is that for "qqqq", `s_prime = C B A` would be "qqqq" itself.
    // We need `s_prime != s`.
    // If `s` consists of all same characters, e.g., "aaaaa", then `A="a"`, `B="aaa"`, `C="a"`.
    // `CBA = "a" + "aaa" + "a" = "aaaaa"`, which is `s`.
    // So the condition `s_prime != s` is crucial.
    // For `CBA != ABC`, we need `A != C`.
    // But `s` is a palindrome, so `A = reverse(C)`.
    // Thus `A != C` is equivalent to `A != reverse(A)`, i.e., `A` is not a palindrome.
    // If `s` consists of all same characters, then any `A` (prefix) is a palindrome.
    // So `A == reverse(A)`, which means `A == C`.
    // In this case, `CBA` will always be equal to `ABC`.
    // So if `s` consists of all same characters, `k=2` (using this strategy) will not work.

    // Let's re-evaluate the "Impossible" case.
    // If all characters in `s` are the same, e.g., "aaaaa".
    // Any substring `s.substr(i, len)` is also "aaaa..." and is a palindrome.
    // For `k=1`, `s' = B+A`. If `s` is "aaaaa", `A="a"`, `B="aaaa"`. `s'="aaaaa"`. Always `s' == s`.
    // For `k=2`, `s' = C+B+A`. If `s` is "aaaaa", `A="a"`, `B="aaa"`, `C="a"`. `s'="aaaaa"`. Always `s' == s`.
    // So if all characters are the same, it's impossible.
    bool all_same = true;
    for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
        if (s[i] != s[0]) {
            all_same = false;
            break;
        }
    }

    if (all_same) {
        std::cout << "Impossible" << std::endl;
        return 0;
    }

    // If not all characters are the same, and k=1 didn't work, then k=2 must work.
    // Why? Consider the string `s`. Since it's a palindrome and not all characters are the same,
    // there must be at least two distinct characters.
    // Let `s = c_0 c_1 ... c_{n-1}`.
    // Since `s` is a palindrome, `c_i = c_{n-1-i}`.
    // Since not all characters are the same, there exists some `j` such that `c_j != c_0`.
    // Let `j_min` be the smallest index such that `c_{j_min} != c_0`.
    // Then `s[0...j_min-1]` consists only of `c_0`. This prefix is a palindrome.
    // `s[j_min]` is `c_{j_min}`.
    // Consider `i = 1`. `A = s[0]`, `B = s[1...n-2]`, `C = s[n-1]`.
    // `A` is a palindrome. `C` is a palindrome. `A=C`.
    // If `B` is not a palindrome, then `k=2` is possible by cutting `s` into `s[0] | s[1...n-2] | s[n-1]`
    // and rearranging to `s[n-1] | s[1...n-2] | s[0]`.
    // This new string is `s` itself. This is not what we want.
    // The k=2 strategy that works is:
    // Cut `s` into `s[0...i-1] | s[i...n-1-i] | s[n-i...n-1]`.
    // Let `A = s[0...i-1]`, `B = s[i...n-1-i]`, `C = s[n-i...n-1]`.
    // Since `s` is a palindrome, `A = reverse(C)`.
    // We want to form `C B A`. This will be a palindrome.
    // We need `C B A != A B C`. This means `A != C`.
    // `A != C` implies `A != reverse(A)`, i.e., `A` is not a palindrome.
    // So we need to find an `i` such that `s.substr(0, i)` is NOT a palindrome.
    // If such an `i` exists, then we can use `k=2`.
    // The middle part `B = s.substr(i, n - 2*i)` must be a palindrome.
    // If `n - 2*i < 0`, this `i` is invalid. So `i <= n/2`.
    // If `n - 2*i == 0` or `1`, `B` is a palindrome.
    // If `n - 2*i > 1`, `B` must be a palindrome.

    // The problem statement implies that if k=1 doesn't work, and it's not "Impossible", then k=2 must be the answer.
    // The only case where it's "Impossible" is when all characters are the same.
    // If not all characters are the same, then there must be some `i` such that `s[i] != s[0]`.
    // Consider `s = "nolon"`. `n=5`.
    // `k=1` check:
    // `i=1`: `A="n"`, `B="olon"`. `s'="olonn"`. Not pal.
    // `i=2`: `A="no"`, `B="lon"`. `s'="lonno"`. Not pal.
    // `i=3`: `A="nol"`, `B="on"`. `s'="onnol"`. Not pal.
    // `i=4`: `A="nolo"`, `B="n"`. `s'="nnolo"`. Not pal.
    // So `k=1` fails for "nolon".
    // `k=2` check:
    // `i=1`: `prefix="n"`. Is pal. Skip.
    // `i=2`: `prefix="no"`. Not pal. `middle="l"`. Is pal.
    // Conditions met: `prefix` not pal, `middle` is pal. Output 2.
    // This matches the example.

    // The logic seems to be:
    // 1. Check for k=1. If found, print 1 and exit.
    // 2. Check if all characters in `s` are the same. If so, print "Impossible" and exit.
    // 3. Otherwise (k=1 failed, and not all chars same), print 2.
    // This covers all cases. The k=2 check in the code is actually implicitly covered by the fact that if not all chars are same,
    // there must exist some `i` such that `s.substr(0, i)` is not a palindrome.
    // For example, if `s = "abacaba"`. `n=7`.
    // `k=1` check:
    // `i=1`: `A="a"`, `B="bacaba"`. `s'="bacabaa"`. Not pal.
    // `i=2`: `A="ab"`, `B="acaba"`. `s'="acabaab"`. Not pal.
    // ...
    // `k=1` will fail for "abacaba".
    // All chars are not same. So output 2.
    // Let's verify for "abacaba" that k=2 works.
    // `i=1`: `prefix="a"` (pal). Skip.
    // `i=2`: `prefix="ab"` (not pal). `middle="aca"` (pal). Conditions met. Output 2.
    // This seems correct.

    std::cout << 2 << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
#include <set>

bool check(long long T, int n, int m, const std::vector<long long>& h, const std::vector<long long>& p) {
    std::vector<long long> head_left_reach(n);
    std::vector<long long> head_right_reach(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        head_left_reach[i] = h[i] - T;
        head_right_reach[i] = h[i] + T;
    }

    int p_idx = 0;
    int h_idx = 0;

    while (p_idx < m) {
        if (h_idx >= n) {
            return false; // No more heads to cover remaining points
        }

        // Find the first point p[p_idx] that is not yet covered
        // This loop is actually not needed because p_idx only advances when a point is covered.
        // The main loop structure ensures we are always looking at the first uncovered point.

        // Try to cover p[p_idx] with head h[h_idx]
        if (head_right_reach[h_idx] < p[p_idx]) {
            // This head cannot reach p[p_idx] (it's too far to the left)
            // Move to the next head
            h_idx++;
            continue;
        }

        // If head_left_reach[h_idx] > p[p_idx], this head is too far to the right to cover p[p_idx]
        // This means p[p_idx] cannot be covered by h[h_idx] or any subsequent head (since h is sorted).
        // This case should ideally not happen if we are trying to cover p[p_idx] with the "best" head.
        // However, the greedy strategy is to use the current head h[h_idx] to cover as many points as possible
        // starting from p[p_idx].

        // If head_left_reach[h_idx] <= p[p_idx] <= head_right_reach[h_idx],
        // then h[h_idx] can cover p[p_idx].
        // We use this head to cover p[p_idx] and all subsequent points it can reach.
        long long current_head_max_reach = head_right_reach[h_idx];
        while (p_idx < m && p[p_idx] <= current_head_max_reach) {
            p_idx++;
        }
        h_idx++; // Move to the next head for the remaining points
    }

    return true; // All points covered
}

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);

    int n, m;
    std::cin >> n >> m;

    std::vector<long long> h(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cin >> h[i];
    }

    std::vector<long long> p(m);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
        std::cin >> p[i];
    }

    long long low = 0;
    long long high = 20000000000LL; // Max possible difference between coordinates is 10^10.
                                    // A head might need to move from 1 to 10^10, so T can be 10^10.
                                    // 2 * 10^10 is a safe upper bound.
    long long ans = high;

    while (low <= high) {
        long long mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
        if (check(mid, n, m, h, p)) {
            ans = mid;
            high = mid - 1;
        } else {
            low = mid + 1;
        }
    }

    std::cout << ans << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
#include <numeric>

struct Element {
    long long value;
    int original_index;
};

bool compareElements(const Element& a, const Element& b) {
    return a.value < b.value;
}

int main() {
    std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
    std::cin.tie(NULL);

    int n;
    long long h;
    std::cin >> n >> h;

    std::vector<Element> elements(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cin >> elements[i].value;
        elements[i].original_index = i;
    }

    std::sort(elements.begin(), elements.end(), compareElements);

    long long min_goodness = -1;
    std::vector<int> best_partition(n);

    // Case 1: All elements in one subsequence (or one empty, one full)
    // This means all f(a_i, a_j) = a_i + a_j.
    // min_f = a_1 + a_2
    // max_f = a_{n-1} + a_n
    // Goodness = (a_{n-1} + a_n) - (a_1 + a_2)
    long long current_goodness_case1 = (elements[n - 1].value + elements[n - 2].value) - (elements[0].value + elements[1].value);
    min_goodness = current_goodness_case1;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        best_partition[elements[i].original_index] = 1;
    }

    // Case 2: Partition into two non-empty subsequences.
    // The minimum possible f value is a_1 + a_2.
    // The maximum possible f value is max(a_{n-1} + a_n, a_1 + a_n + h).
    // This occurs if a_1 and a_n are in different subsequences.
    // If a_1 and a_n are in different subsequences, then a_1 + a_n + h is a candidate for max_f.
    // If a_1 and a_n are in the same subsequence, then a_1 + a_n is a candidate for max_f.
    //
    // Consider a partition where elements[0] is in subseq 1, and elements[n-1] is in subseq 2.
    // And elements[n-2] is in subseq 2.
    // The minimum f value is elements[0].value + elements[1].value (if elements[0] and elements[1] are in same subseq)
    // OR elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h (if elements[0] and elements[1] are in different subseq)
    //
    // Let's analyze the minimum and maximum values of f more carefully.
    // min_f is always a_1 + a_2 (if a_1, a_2 are in same subseq) or a_1 + a_2 + h (if a_1, a_2 are in different subseq).
    // max_f is always a_{n-1} + a_n (if a_{n-1}, a_n are in same subseq) or a_{n-1} + a_n + h (if a_{n-1}, a_n are in different subseq).
    //
    // The crucial observation is that if we put elements[0] into one subsequence (say, 1)
    // and elements[n-1] into another subsequence (say, 2), then the value elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h
    // is a candidate for max_f.
    //
    // What if we put elements[0] into subsequence 1, and all other elements into subsequence 2?
    // Subsequence 1: {elements[0]}
    // Subsequence 2: {elements[1], ..., elements[n-1]}
    //
    // Values of f:
    // 1. Pairs within Subsequence 2: elements[i].value + elements[j].value for i,j in [1, n-1]
    //    Min: elements[1].value + elements[2].value
    //    Max: elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value
    // 2. Pairs across subsequences: elements[0].value + elements[j].value + h for j in [1, n-1]
    //    Min: elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h
    //    Max: elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h
    //
    // Overall min_f for this partition: min(elements[1].value + elements[2].value, elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h)
    // Overall max_f for this partition: max(elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value, elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h)
    //
    // This partition strategy is: elements[0] in subseq 1, elements[1...n-1] in subseq 2.
    // The minimum possible sum is elements[0].value + elements[1].value.
    // If elements[0] and elements[1] are in different subsequences, this sum becomes elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h.
    // If elements[0] and elements[1] are in the same subsequence, this sum is elements[0].value + elements[1].value.
    //
    // In the proposed partition (elements[0] in 1, others in 2):
    // min_f = min(elements[1].value + elements[2].value, elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h)
    // max_f = max(elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value, elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h)
    //
    // The goodness for this partition is max_f - min_f.
    //
    // Let's consider the specific partition:
    // elements[0] is in subsequence 1.
    // elements[1], ..., elements[n-1] are in subsequence 2.
    //
    // min_f:
    //   - If n=2: elements[0] in 1, elements[1] in 2. Only one pair (0,1). f = elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h.
    //     min_f = max_f = elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h. Goodness = 0.
    //   - If n > 2:
    //     Pairs within subseq 2: (elements[1], elements[2]) -> elements[1].value + elements[2].value
    //     Pairs across subseqs: (elements[0], elements[1]) -> elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h
    //     So, min_f = std::min(elements[1].value + elements[2].value, elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h)
    //
    // max_f:
    //   - If n=2: elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h.
    //   - If n > 2:
    //     Pairs within subseq 2: (elements[n-1], elements[n-2]) -> elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value
    //     Pairs across subseqs: (elements[0], elements[n-1]) -> elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h
    //     So, max_f = std::max(elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value, elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h)
    //
    // This partition is only relevant if n > 2. If n=2, the goodness is 0, which is always optimal.
    // The case n=2 is covered by Case 1 (goodness = (a_1+a_2)-(a_1+a_2) = 0).
    // So we only need to consider n > 2 for this specific partition.

    if (n > 2) {
        long long current_min_f_case2 = std::min(elements[1].value + elements[2].value, elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h);
        long long current_max_f_case2 = std::max(elements[n - 1].value + elements[n - 2].value, elements[0].value + elements[n - 1].value + h);
        long long current_goodness_case2 = current_max_f_case2 - current_min_f_case2;

        if (current_goodness_case2 < min_goodness) {
            min_goodness = current_goodness_case2;
            best_partition[elements[0].original_index] = 1;
            for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
                best_partition[elements[i].original_index] = 2;
            }
        }
    }

    // The third case is when elements[0] and elements[1] are in different subsequences,
    // and elements[n-1] and elements[n-2] are in the same subsequence.
    // This means elements[0] is in subseq 1, elements[1] is in subseq 2.
    // And elements[n-1] and elements[n-2] are both in subseq 2.
    //
    // Consider the partition:
    // elements[0] in subseq 1.
    // elements[1], ..., elements[n-1] in subseq 2.
    // This is exactly Case 2.
    //
    // What if elements[0] and elements[1] are in different subsequences,
    // AND elements[n-1] and elements[n-2] are in different subsequences?
    // e.g., elements[0] in 1, elements[1] in 2.
    //       elements[n-1] in 1, elements[n-2] in 2.
    // This is getting complicated.
    //
    // Let's simplify the analysis of min_f and max_f.
    //
    // The minimum possible sum of two elements is `elements[0].value + elements[1].value`.
    // The maximum possible sum of two elements is `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value`.
    //
    // The minimum `f` value is either `elements[0].value + elements[1].value` or `elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h`.
    // The maximum `f` value is either `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value` or `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value + h`.
    //
    // Also, `elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h` is a potential maximum if `elements[0]` and `elements[n-1]` are separated.
    // And `elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value` is a potential maximum if `elements[0]` and `elements[n-1]` are together.
    //
    // The key insight for these problems is often that the optimal partition involves the extreme elements.
    //
    // Let's consider the minimum possible `f` value. It's either `elements[0].value + elements[1].value` or `elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h`.
    // Let's consider the maximum possible `f` value. It's either `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value` or `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value + h`.
    // Also, `elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h` is a strong candidate for max_f if elements[0] and elements[n-1] are separated.
    //
    // There are only a few "critical" values for `f`:
    // A = elements[0].value + elements[1].value
    // B = elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value
    // C = elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value
    //
    // Possible min_f values: A, A+h
    // Possible max_f values: B, B+h, C+h (if elements[0] and elements[n-1] are separated)
    //
    // Let's consider the partition where elements[0] is in subseq 1, and all other elements are in subseq 2.
    // This is the partition we analyzed as Case 2.
    //
    // What if elements[0] and elements[n-1] are in the same subsequence?
    // Then elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value is a value of f.
    // And elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h is NOT a value of f.
    //
    // If elements[0] and elements[n-1] are in the same subsequence (say, 1),
    // and elements[1] is in subsequence 2.
    // Then elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h is a value of f.
    // And elements[n-1].value + elements[1].value + h is a value of f.
    //
    // The minimum possible value of f is always `elements[0].value + elements[1].value` or `elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h`.
    // The maximum possible value of f is always `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value` or `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value + h`.
    //
    // Let's consider the partition where elements[0] is in subseq 1, and elements[1] is in subseq 2.
    // All other elements (elements[2]...elements[n-1]) can be assigned to either subseq 1 or 2.
    // To minimize the range, we want to make the max_f as small as possible and min_f as large as possible.
    //
    // If elements[0] is in 1, elements[1] is in 2:
    // Then elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h is definitely a value of f. This is a candidate for min_f.
    //
    // What if we put elements[0] in subseq 1, and elements[1]...elements[n-1] in subseq 2? (This is Case 2)
    // min_f = min(elements[1].value + elements[2].value, elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h)
    // max_f = max(elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value, elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h)
    //
    // What if we put elements[0] and elements[1] in subseq 1, and elements[2]...elements[n-1] in subseq 2?
    // This is not necessarily better.
    //
    // The problem states that one subsequence can be empty. Case 1 covers this.
    //
    // The crucial observation is that the minimum value of `f` is either `elements[0].value + elements[1].value`
    // or `elements[0].value + elements[1].value + h`.
    // The maximum value of `f` is either `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value`
    // or `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value + h`.
    //
    // However, there's a third candidate for max_f: `elements[0].value + elements[n-1].value + h`
    // if `elements[0]` and `elements[n-1]` are in different subsequences.
    //
    // Let's consider two main scenarios for the optimal partition:
    //
    // Scenario A: All elements are in the same subsequence.
    //   min_f = elements[0].value + elements[1].value
    //   max_f = elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value
    //   Goodness = (elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value) - (elements[0].value + elements[1].value)
    //   This is `current_goodness_case1`.
    //
    // Scenario B: Elements are split into two non-empty subsequences.
    //   To minimize the goodness, we want to make `min_f` as large as possible and `max_f` as small as possible.
    //   The smallest possible sum is `elements[0].value + elements[1].value`.
    //   The largest possible sum is `elements[n-1].value + elements[n-2].value`.
